<subSubSection lastPageId="41" pageId="39" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="39.[718,1247,1217,1768]" pageId="39">
DIAGNOSIS: Males of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="BOSSELAERS &amp; JOCQUÉ" authorityYear="2000" box="[1010,1139,1481,1504]" class="Arachnida" family="Corinnidae" genus="Hortipes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="scharffi">
<emphasis box="[1010,1139,1481,1504]" italics="true" pageId="39">H. scharffi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are recognized by the very long and slender RTA, strongly curved backward. Males are similar to those of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="BOSSELAERS &amp; JOCQUÉ" authorityYear="2000" box="[858,1008,1569,1592]" class="Arachnida" family="Corinnidae" genus="Hortipes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cucurbita">
<emphasis box="[858,1008,1569,1592]" italics="true" pageId="39">H. cucurbita</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but in that species the RTA is not recurved but simply curved down. Females can be recognized by the gourd­shaped ST1 and the ID having a hairpin loop associated with a glandular structure and making a U­loop in a ventral direction before connecting to ST1.
</paragraph>
